<h3>Software Stability = 2</h3>
<p>Conventions; Here today, outdated tomorrow.  The tale of a never-ending moving target.  The trade-off with constantly progressing
software is the reality that things must change to improve.  The current reality of staying on-top of Emberjs is that its a full-time
job. Like guides/support, i'd rather have the limited resources spent on building the best damn software ever and worry about the docs
/ guides once things have settled down + stabilized. Forgiveness does not take way from the degree of frustration many have felt over
the years with topics like Ember-Datas Forever-Beta and HTMLBars.  Their tardiness record that will make ferris bueller appear punctual.</p>
<h3>Integrations = 3</h3>
<p>	Day by day more players in the software community are making sure their products integrate with ember.  That said, most/many still
  lead with an Angular integration (Ionic, Foundation) with Ember as an afterthought.  That should change soon, but currently
  integrations have room to improve.</p>
<h3>Community = 5</h3>
<p>Ember has a high quality community and the overall theme of the community is helpful, talented and passionate about open source
software.  The official core-team has exceptional core-team talent such as – Yaheuda, Tom Dale, Matt Beale, Luke Melia, Robert Jackson,
 Stefan Penner, Erik Bryn, Edward Faulkner, Toran Billups, Trek Glowacki, Peter Wagenet, Leah Silber, Alex Matchneer and Kris Selden.
  Contributions from the likes of Martin Genev, Adolfo Biles, Lauren Tan, Godfrey Chan, Taras Mankowski cannot be understimated.</p>
<h3>Staying Power = 5</h3>
<p>	Many Powerful and trusted companies that advocate using Emberjs include Yahoo, LinkedIn, Groupon, Netflix, Bustle and Mozilla.
  Their investments financially as well as internally should ensure Ember will be around at least a few years.</p>

